caption:
Hey Pregnant Mummies Do you know that you can get up to $13,000 of Cash Gift & (CDA) benefits under the Baby Bonus Scheme? Your newborn child may be eligible for the Baby Bonus if: - he or she is a Singapore Citizen - and if the parents are lawfully married You can join the Scheme on behalf of your child as early as 2 months before their estimated delivery date. Now, letâ€™s talk about the Cash Gift first. For your 1st and 2nd child, the Cash Gift amount you can receive is $11,000. While for your 3rd and subsequent child, is $13,000. After joining the Scheme, you can expect to receive the 1st instalment of the cash gift within 7 to 10 working days of your child's birth registration. The remaining instalments are then disbursed every 6 months till your child turns six-and-a-half years old. (will show table below on reel)(voiceover)
And you can use the cash gift freely to pay for your child's expenses. Next, letâ€™s talk about the benefits of (CDA) Child Development Account (CDA) is a special savings account that you can open for your child at any of these banks. (will list out the banks on reel) (voiceover) So Whatâ€™s so special about this saving account? 1st, the Government will deposit $5,000 into this account.
2nd, you can enjoy dollar-for-dollar matching from the Government when you save into this account, up to the Govt co-matching cap of $4,000 - $15,000. You can save & use the funds until 31st Dec of the year your child turns 12 years old. Lastly the funds can be used for many purposes at many places. Visit our website on what the money can be used on.

caption:
ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ³ó £ó ´ó ¿ MILLIONAIRE SHORTBREAD ğŸ´ó §ó ¢ó ³ó £ó ´ó ¿
This was my ultimate fave tray bake when I was a kid, and I have been asked for this recipe so many times! I was looking through mums old recipe book from the 70s & 80s and found this old supplement on traybakes. The language used is so old fashioned, but the recipes are still true. I only tweaked this slightly, but checked with mum and it was the recipe she used when we were kids! Thankyou to whatever magazine or newspaper this originally came from, itâ€™s damn delicious! Fills an 8â€ x 10â€ (20 x 26cm) tin
Shortbread 150g plain flour/50g corn flour (starch)- sifted 160g butter (softened)
85g caster sugar
Pinch salt
Combine all ingredients in a stand mixer with a paddle attachment and mix till combined. Roll out to a rough rectangle no bigger than your greased tin and place within. Cut to fit using excess to fill corners. Prick all over with a fork and bake at 160c (fan forced) for 20 mins. Cool in tin.
Caramel
160g butter
160g soft brown sugar
395g tin sweetened condensed milk
3 tbsp golden syrup
1 tsp smoked salt flakes
Few drops vanilla essence
Put all ingredients apart from salt and vanilla into a saucepan and heat gently till combined. Simmer and stir for at least 10-15 minutes till darker in colour & thickened. Add the salt and vanilla essence and mix well, pour carefully over the shortbread and tap tin on worktop to distribute evenly. Pop into fridge to set.
Once set, melt 80g of each plain and dark chocolate. Stir thoroughly then pour over the caramel. Tap tap tap on worktop to level out and back in fridge to set.
Using a sharp knife cut into squares and enjoy! I like keeping mine in fridge - enjoy â˜ºï¸ #shortbread #millionaire #caramel #chocolate #rovinghaggis

caption:
Sharing my quick weekday dinner fix!

Using Unagi in Teriyaki Sauce from @theseafoodcompany.sg , I can whip up a dinner real quick on a busy weekday evening ğŸ˜

SEACO Unagi comes in a frozen ready to eat pack. I just airfry it for about 10 mins, fry an omelette , some sliced cucumbers and put them altogether in a bowl and dinner is served! 

My kids love Unagi! 

Unagi, the Japanese eel contains a great assortment of vitamins and minerals, including vitamins A, D, E, B1, B2, B12 and phosphorous. 
This mineral is especially important to health because it helps to balance your bodyâ€™s PH levels, improve digestion and metabolism, and enable the body to better absorb nutrients.
Unagi is also high in omega-3. It helps to improve blood pressure, lower cholesterol and reduce the risks of diabetes and arthritis. So it's really a great food for everyone in the family.

Receipe ( Serves 1 )

1 fillet of Seaco Frozen Unagi in Teriyaki Sauce
1 egg
1 Cucumber 
1 bowl of cooked rice
Furikake and Sesame seeds for toppings

1. Airfry 1 fillet of Seaco Unagi in Teriyaki sauce for about 10 mins
2. Fry an egg omelette 
3. Sliced some cucumbers
4. Place the airfried unagi, egg omelette and cucumbers on top of a bowl of cooked rice and sprinkle with some furikake and roasted sesame seeds.

Dinner is ready!

Love that homecooked dinner can be ready in no time!

Showcasing at the National Museum of Singapore, it is the first global showcase outside of Japan.

Showcasing Doraemon through the lens of 28 leading contemporary Japanese artists & arts groups, the artworks on display respond to the theme of â€œCreate Your Own Original Doraemonâ€.

Featuring distinctive artworks that capture the artistsâ€™ memories of Doraemon & their take on Doraemon, the exhibition presents a diverse mix of ideas, mediums & techniques that include paintings, sculptures, graphics & photography. 2 artworks by Singaporean artists are also exclusively presented as part of this showcase.

The Singapore edition of the exhibition also features a selection of the Fujiko F Fujio Museumâ€™s prized drawings & sketches by the late Doraemon creator Mr Fujiko, in a rare feature titled â€œMANGA DORAEMON Original Drawings Exhibitionâ€ - Act 3!

You can also look forward to exciting complementary offerings including a pop-up cafÃ© and a retail experience with limited edition Doraemon collectibles.

There are a total of 3 Acts! I personally love Act 2 the most! Do note that Act 3 does not allow any photography except for the photo spot within. Tickets are sold at $30 per adult and $25 for those under 18. Kids below 6 are free! Itâ€™s open from 10am to 7pm so do pop by real soon! You will have a dorae-ffic time there!

caption:
Sharing my quick weekday dinner fix!

Using Unagi in Teriyaki Sauce from @theseafoodcompany.sg , I can whip up a dinner real quick on a busy weekday evening ğŸ˜

SEACO Unagi comes in a frozen ready to eat pack. I just airfry it for about 10 mins, fry an omelette , some sliced cucumbers and put them altogether in a bowl and dinner is served! 

My kids love Unagi! 

Unagi, the Japanese eel contains a great assortment of vitamins and minerals, including vitamins A, D, E, B1, B2, B12 and phosphorous. 
This mineral is especially important to health because it helps to balance your bodyâ€™s PH levels, improve digestion and metabolism, and enable the body to better absorb nutrients.
Unagi is also high in omega-3. It helps to improve blood pressure, lower cholesterol and reduce the risks of diabetes and arthritis. So it's really a great food for everyone in the family.

Receipe ( Serves 1 )

1 fillet of Seaco Frozen Unagi in Teriyaki Sauce
1 egg
1 Cucumber 
1 bowl of cooked rice
Furikake and Sesame seeds for toppings

1. Airfry 1 fillet of Seaco Unagi in Teriyaki sauce for about 10 mins
2. Fry an egg omelette 
3. Sliced some cucumbers
4. Place the airfried unagi, egg omelette and cucumbers on top of a bowl of cooked rice and sprinkle with some furikake and roasted sesame seeds.

Dinner is ready!

Love that homecooked dinner can be ready in no time!

caption:
Kid's friendly -- Milky Miso macaroni soup

Super simple but flavourful dish for Gwen. I'm using scallop and salmon for this dish, but you can also make this soup with chicken and any proteins. Ohh, now then I realise miso pair so well with milk. It can be one of our comfort dish!

Ingredients:
1/2 cup macaroni 
1/2 cup carrots
500ml water (add occasionally)
20g cubed salmon
1 scallop
Gomoku Nama Age or fried toufu
Enoki mushrooms 
2 tablespoons fresh milk

UPDATES: Stir in the miso paste after adding the milk. 

I Google after got to know that miso mixture should be added at the final stage of cooking. The nutritional benefits are damaged once it's boiled because miso is a fermented food, and it contains live, active cultures of bacteria. Thanks for letting me know about it! I shall take note ğŸ«

For the fishing, the hooks are sharp and little hands would not be as adept to work on it. Careful cos smaller kids may have the hook near eye level too. We mainly threw the fish feed into the pond so it was safer.

caption:
Letâ€™s start practicing good eye care habits to prevent or slow down childhood myopia! We can do this, fellow mums & dads! â¤ï¸

More than half of children developing myopia by 12 years old and the scary part here is childhood myopia tends to progress quickly and it leads to higher levels of myopia and more eye health risks! 

Thankfully, we have the Amanda the Panda book to help us with tips for myopia management which we are going to share with you too! Because sharing is caring! â¤ï¸

1. Letâ€™s go out and have fun outdoor activities instead of staying indoors all the time. It can help to delay onset of myopia.
2. Bring your children for eye check-ups even they donâ€™t wear glasses. Book here: www.snec.com.sg/myopia-centre 
3. Letâ€™s encourage your children to relax their eyes for 3 to 5 minutes after half an hour of doing homework, reading or using electronic device 
4. Wear a pair of sunglasses with UV protection to shield childrenâ€™s eyes from excessive ultraviolet rays 
5. Remember to light up adequately with a table lamp to reduce eye strain 
6. Read from a distance - at least 35cm. 50-60cm away from the computer and 2 metres or further from television 
7. Maintaining good posture is important. Consider ergonomics desk! 
8. Protective eye wear is great to prevent eye injuries when playing sports 
9. For myopic children, do consult eye care professional for advice on myopia management solution to prevent it from worsening.

Thanks to Amanda, The Panda ğŸ¼ for teaching us more tips on myopia management and now Iâ€™m letting my kids to have fun adventures playing outdoors. My youngest kid loves her fun bubble play and itâ€™s nice to enjoy fresh air while spending precious moment with the little ones! â¤ï¸

caption:
Last weekend, we went on a mission to collect all the 3 National Day Commerative Special Collectibles. 

We earned our 1st commerative coin when we went to @westmallsg . The girl had to go through the various army stations and get all the questionnaires correct. They got to try out wearing the army vest, The girls had fun going through the various game stations.

Secondly, we earned our second commerative coin at @singaporediscoverycentre The girls had fun making their own gasing. They also viewed the various displays inside. The girls also tried their hands on the 3D military games, each taking a role as an Airforce fighter pilot, a Army tank commander and a Navy combat ship commander, all doing their part to destroy enemy intruders! We had fun learning about Singapore.

Finally we earned our 3rd commerative coin at @singaporenavymuseum . The girls get to learn more about Singapore's Maritime History and how we have progressed over the decades. The girls had fun learning about our Maritime history, Semaphore Flag Codes, history of the RSN and more! 

Just a suggestion to drive there as there is no public transport and unlikely that taxi and private hired cars will go all the way there to pick you. We saw and heard a few families "stranded" there for a while because they couldnt get transport out. 

The commerative event is until 13Aug. Here are the websites of the 3 venues that we went. Click on the link to find out more.

Wishing everyone Happy National Day! ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬

name: Ester Voon
caption:
Having live-in domestic help is something we are all familiar with in Singapore but a concept many others in the rest of the world find highly privileged. And after dealing with the bull that some of my ex helpers have given me, I first toyed with the idea of going without any domestic helpers around mid 2022. I told myself that if the two helpers I had at that time didnâ€™t last, then it would be the last of my search efforts for a helper that would fit my householdâ€™s needs. To pave the way for this possible outcome, I started to slow down my own business and started planning for my transition to being a full time SAHM.

Fast forward to end June 2023, I sent home my last helper. I was a little fearful NGL, afterall I have never lived a day without having fewer than 2 extra hired pair of helping hands at home since I got married and started a family. My mum and mil who have been also a constant source of support and help with the kids had serious concerns. They repeatedly advised me against going without helpers and to reconsider hiring just one more so I wouldnâ€™t â€œdrown and dieâ€. But my heart was set. Afterall thereâ€™s nothing I enjoy doing more than the things people think I cannot. 

I struggled, I did. But I also survived. Now 3 months into my days as a SAHM to 3 girls without any hired help, I can say that this has been the best thing I have done for our family.

My kids are still well fed and well dressed, my house is still clean and aesthetic (if I may say so myself) as hellâ€¦ my mind is peaceful, I love the privacy, my husband has stepped up and became the hands on daddy of our dreams, and we have so much more time spent together with our kids. 

So hereâ€™s a reminder that âœ¨when you think that you can do no more, give no moreâ€¦ there is always more in you if you dig deeper. Nothing is truly impossibleâœ¨ it hurts a little to put my own aspirations on hold and Iâ€™m beyond exhausted most days but Iâ€™d still make the same decision again in a heartbeat. Itâ€™s truly so worth it.

#mumlife #mumsg #justdoit #sahmlife

caption:
We had lots of fun today cooling off at Splash-N-Surf, which is located on top of Kallang Wave Mall. Here you can find:

ğŸ”·ï¸ Kids Water Play Area - which consists of a range of water slides and water fountains.
ğŸ”·ï¸ Kids Pool - which is a 60cm deep pool & has a set of bucket water swings.
ğŸ”·ï¸ Lazy River - is 1m deep and has a gentle current so you can laze in a tube and float around the pool. What's great is they even have some little tubes suitable for toddlers.

ğŸ“ Splash-N-Surf, Level 3 Kallang Wave Mall Near gate 21 of National, stadium, 397629 Singapore 

â°ï¸ Mon, Wed, Thurs, Fri, Sat & Sun 9am to 8pm. Closed every Tues, selected public holidays (eg New Years Day, 1st day Chinese New Year, Hari Raya Puasa, Deepavali & Christmas) & it is also closed other times as published on https://www.sportshub.com.sg/announcement/splash-n-surf 
During rain, I would call before visiting to check they are still open (as I know some water play areas shut during rain).

ğŸ¤‘ The kids water play area & kids pool are FREE! The Lazy river is $2 per person, and you get to use a float. Note you can ride the lazy river as many times as you like and can even leave and re-enter on the same day.

ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ‘©â€ğŸ‘¦ The kids water play area and kids pool are for kids 12 and under (with supervising adults). These areas are probably most suited for those under 6 as I think older kids may get bored (although I have received comments from others that older kids under 10 still enjoy the area). The lazy river is for everyone (again with supervising adults).

caption:
Calling first time moms struggling with in-laws questioning your parenting.

You tell yourself they mean well.
You tell yourself itâ€™s just for a season.
But somehow, every bottle, every nap schedule, every decisionâ€”suddenly feels like itâ€™s not yours anymore.

And the worst part? You feel guilty for feeling upset AND for not stepping in earlier.

Here are 5 ways in-laws quietly take over, leaving new moms feeling smallâ€”and what you can do about it:

1. They make themselves the â€œdefault expert.â€
They say things like â€œThis is how we did it,â€ or â€œBack in my dayâ€¦â€ as if your instincts donâ€™t count.

ğŸ“Œ Try this: â€œThanks for sharing. Weâ€™ve decided to follow our paediatricianâ€™s advice on this.â€
(Gottman calls this setting a unified front. It buffers against external stress and helps to build the couple as a team.)

2. They step in before you can.
Feeding the baby, burping the baby, putting them to sleepâ€¦ all before youâ€™ve had a chance.

ğŸ“Œ Try this: â€œI appreciate the help, but Iâ€™d like to do this myself today.â€
(As Nedra Glover Tawwab says: Boundaries are not just walls, theyâ€™re clarity. Telling your in law that even if it takes you longer, you'd like to handle these baby caregiving yourself provides clarity.)

3. They question your routines subtly.
â€œIsnâ€™t it too early for solids?â€ or â€œShe naps again?â€

ğŸ“Œ Try this: â€œWeâ€™re trying what works for us. Itâ€™s okay if it looks different.â€
(BrenÃ© Brown reminds us that clear is kind. Vague boundaries invite confusion.)

P.S. Even if YOU feel unsure and like you're still figuring out, it's okay to still have boundaries. 
ğŸ‘‰ Youâ€™re just adjusting to your new identity as a momâ€”while trying to hold on to your voice.

Your baby doesnâ€™t just need love.

caption:
When my baby needs a cuddle and clings onto me like a little koala ğŸ¨ 

She's happy to be in my arms and accompanying me while I dry my hair.. to which I say to her, "Thank you for being so patient and waiting for mummy."
- - - 
Day 77 | Bathed Tia myself for the first time today, under granny's guidance ğŸ›

Pep talked my darling that mummy will be the one bathing her today. Asked for her patience with me, which she so kindly gave. There was no fussing as her clumsy mummy fumbled and stumbled with awkward angles and holds. Despite all that, she looked at me all starry-eyed, smiling.. aww~ *melts into a puddle*

And I said to her, "Thank you for being so patient with mummy. Mummy will get better at this. Sorry for taking too long."

It's amazing how there's someone who can make me say "thank you" and "sorry" all the time, so wholeheartedly and willingly..

I love you, Tia. So so much. 
Thank you for coming into our life.
